node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Behemot on August 06, 2021. May be an illustration.

node.text:
Only high concept art here 🖤 tag yourself!
.
Just a small reminder that I'm having a sale in my print shop, everything is 20% off with code IXHIBO! There's a big selection of prints, so hit the link in bio and treat yourself! I have some new art there, as well as some old fan favourites so I'm sure you'll find something cool. Thank you all for all the support.
.
P. S. Answering all emails by the end of the week!
.

node.text:
Vampire boy character 🦇 which one do you prefer?
.
We all know that the angles are essential in character design. I’m sure you’d often hear the “rule” that protagonists are drawn in smoother lines and antagonists in more angular ones. This is done mostly because our brains recognise smooth lines as more friendly. They are more natural, more human, while the sharper angels are not so often found in nature and our brains perceive them as something “artificial”, mechanical and cold. I understand the logic behind it, but I find this rule to be a bit misleading. Because, you see, it’s not just the lines and angles that paint the picture of a character, it’s also the PROPORTIONS that those lines create. Take this Vampire boy for example - done in two different ways with completely different lines, but the proportions are exactly the same. He didn’t somehow magically become a villain in the second version, did he? So this post is just a reminder that both lines AND proportions are essential for telling who your character is. You can combine them in the most fun ways to create a whole spectrum of great characters that will successfully communicate with your audience.
.
.
